    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What makes an executive resume different</h2>
      <p>An executive resume is fundamentally different from a mid-level resume — not just in length or format, but in what it is trying to communicate. Where a mid-level resume proves individual contribution, an executive resume proves organizational leadership: how many people, what scope of budget, which business outcomes, and what scale of decision-making.</p>
      <p>Most executive candidates undersell themselves by writing about what they managed rather than what they changed. The best executive resumes show the delta — what was different because of your presence — not just the territory you were responsible for.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What executive resume writers look for</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Leadership scope: team size, budget ownership, org-level decisions</li>
        <li>Business impact: revenue, cost, efficiency, and strategic outcomes</li>
        <li>Trajectory signal: progression of scope and accountability over time</li>
        <li>Cross-functional influence: board, C-suite, and external stakeholder engagement</li>
        <li>Change and transformation: what you built, fixed, or changed at scale</li>
        <li>Market positioning: how your background reads relative to the specific next-level role</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

