      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Executive resume writing — common questions</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-grid">
      <details class="faq-card" open>
        <summary>How long should an executive resume be?</summary>
        <p>Two pages for most executives. Three pages is acceptable for very senior roles (C-suite, SVP+) with genuinely broad scope that requires more context. One page is almost always too short for executive-level work — the depth of scope, impact, and trajectory cannot be communicated effectively in one page at the Director level and above.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-card">
        <summary>How is executive resume writing different from a regular resume revision?</summary>
        <p>Executive resume writing focuses on leadership signal rather than technical or functional skill. The language shifts from "I built" and "I managed" to "I led," "I scaled," "I transformed." The metrics shift from individual output to organizational impact. The narrative shifts from career history to executive trajectory. These are not cosmetic changes — they require different framing from the ground up.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-card">
        <summary>How do I know if my executive resume is working?</summary>
        <p>The most reliable signal is recruiter outreach. If senior recruiters are not proactively reaching out through LinkedIn, and if your applications to Director+ roles are not generating callbacks, the resume is almost certainly the problem — or the LinkedIn profile, which recruiters check before responding to applications. Askia's executive resume service includes LinkedIn alignment to fix both simultaneously.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

